For {= crm_profile =}+ public legal CRM product-profile cases, name at least {= legal_context =}+ legal-practice context per profile and supply {= url =}+ legal-practice context URL for each such context.

Each product profile is a product-documentable unit: a source-stated CRM solution, legal CRM platform, legaltech module, or comparable product family joined to one coherent reusable legal CRM workflow and one reusable CRM data profile that can be corroborated from product or workflow documentation as the same unit. Keep `crm_data_profile` to a short product-data label: normally one primary object or record family, or at most two tightly bound source-stated data families from the same workflow/module. Do not copy every benefit, outcome, metric, role, document type, communication channel, payment item, analytics item, dashboard, automation, or implementation detail from a customer story into one profile. If the legal-context page mentions several modules such as intake, billing, documents, signatures, payments, reporting, and analytics, choose the source-local product-data unit that is visibly central and product-documentable, or split only when the page separately frames materially distinct reusable workflows and data units. The legal-practice context is the law firm, legal department, practitioner, team, role/function group, professional domain, or comparable legal actor whose public context page shows the profile being used or described in concrete legal work. Suitable legal-practice context pages can include original customer/practitioner case studies, law-firm or legal-department practice pages, legal-operations or practitioner articles, association/training sources, focused legal-industry articles, or implementation writeups with concrete practice facts. Generic CRM supplier homepages, product feature pages, by-role or practice-area marketing pages, help-center pages, admin setup articles, API references, generic field/property docs, data dictionaries, job advertisements, recruiting pages, role-opening PDFs, third-party job-board mirrors, third-party case-study aggregators, testimonial repositories, customer-story directories, rehosted case-study pages, rankings, listicles, and directories do not count as legal-practice context sources by themselves. The target is public evidence for legal CRM product profiles in practice context, not hiring responsibility inventories, recommended dropdowns, product comparisons, supplier rankings, outreach lists, lead scoring, contact enrichment, legal advice, procurement advice, implementation adequacy, or bulk harvesting from case-study repositories.

A valid CRM solution is specific enough to pair the legal-practice context with a product/workflow data source. Broad labels such as "CRM", "legal CRM", "law firm software", or "case management software" are not enough by themselves. A valid legal actor is more specific than a broad customer segment. Legal operations, law-firm marketing and business development, attorneys, partners, paralegals, general counsel, CRM managers, conflicts analysts, legal project managers, named firms or departments, and comparable legal functions or role families can be valid. Phrases such as "law firms", "legal teams", "corporate legal departments", or "the legal industry" are not valid by themselves unless the context names a role, function, team, professional domain, or concrete customer/practice setting.

A valid CRM workflow is a concrete legal-sector use case for CRM, client relationships, intake, matter/case lifecycle management, business-development pipeline, relationship intelligence, conflicts, referral management, marketing campaigns, billing/trust/payment work, tasks/deadlines, document/request workflows, reporting, or comparable legal data work. A valid CRM data profile is the source's own reusable, product-documentable data unit for that workflow, such as client relationship records, intake pipeline records, matter/case records, referral records, billing or trust records, task/deadline records, document/request records, campaign/source records, relationship-intelligence records, or a similarly short object/record family. Use wording that can be quoted or directly supported by the cited legal-context source and later by a product/workflow source; if the source only anchors intake forms and matter records, do not add agreements, e-signatures, payment requests, owners, dashboards, reminders, reports, or analytics unless those are source-stated as part of the same compact product-data unit. Case-specific outcomes, customer metrics, practice-area facts, implementation quotes, and actor-specific details can explain the legal context, but they are not part of `crm_data_profile` unless the page frames them as reusable product data structures. A narrow product-control label, isolated UI state, one-off automation action, generic API control, single generic CRM property, dashboard metric alone, or source-specific quote theme is insufficient by itself. A single customer story, implementation writeup, or focused article should usually mint one product profile for its primary product-documentable workflow/data profile. It can mint separate profiles only when the source separately frames materially different solutions, workflows, legal actors/functions, or reusable data profiles; different headings, benefits, automations, reports, stages, user groups, or field lists inside that same deployment are not by themselves materially distinct product profiles.

Requirements:
- The page must visibly earn its stable legal-practice context role for the claimed product profile through source ownership, document context, page title, section framing, byline, practitioner context, original-publisher customer/practitioner case-study context, focused legal-industry publication context, or comparable page-visible cues; generic supplier product promotion, hiring/recruiting surfaces, third-party case-study aggregators, testimonial repositories, customer-story directories, and rehosted case-study pages are insufficient by themselves.
- The page must bind the CRM solution and legal actor to the CRM workflow: it should identify the claimed solution and the claimed legal actor or a clearly same legal-sector function/professional domain, and connect that actor/function to the claimed legal CRM workflow or use case.
- The page must anchor the CRM data profile in the same solution/workflow/legal-context at a product-documentable grain: it should state or clearly describe the primary object/record family, or the tightly bound pair of data families, as part of that source-local legal CRM context. The root source need not be a product manual, but it must provide enough page-local data-use or object/record evidence to select the same compact product-data unit that a product/workflow source can corroborate. Do not inflate the profile into an unrelated deployment-wide bundle, include unsupported extras, or shrink it to an isolated control, field, metric, dashboard, or automation step.
